Replication controller:

 - Replication controller like rc or rs not replicate data between pods. it only maintain containers state.
    1. It maintain pod state.
	   2. High Avaliable
	   3. Scalability

 1. RC (ReplicationController) (Not Recommended)
       => RC is the first controller introcued in k8s.
       => ensures that a specific number of replicas of a pod are running at all times.
       => If Pods exit or are deleted. it will create new replica.
       => Provide pod replication, reliability, LoadBalancing and scalability.
       => RC create by only file method.

 2. RS (ReplicaSet) :
       => Next-generation Replication Controller.
       => A ReplicaSet (RS) in Kubernetes ensures that a specific number of identical pod replicas are running at all times. 
       => If a pod crashes or is deleted, the ReplicaSet automatically replaces it.


   RS vs RC
      => ReplicaSet supports set-based selector, while replication controller only supports equality-based selector.
      => RC is supporting more deployment (rolling-update) strategies.
      => RS create by only file method.

 3. Deployment (Recommended)
      =>

2️⃣ ReplicaSet vs Deployment
Feature	     | ReplicaSet	                                             | Deployment
Purpose      |	Maintains a fixed number of pod replicas	                | Manages rolling updates, rollbacks, and scaling
Updates	     | Requires manual update	                                 | Supports rolling updates & rollbacks
Best         | Use Case	When you only need replication without updates	| When you need rolling updates and version control
Recommended?	| ❌ No (Deployments are preferred)	                      | ✅ Yes (Use Deployment instead)

📌 Deployments internally use ReplicaSets, so using Deployments is the best practice!

--- Example ---

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: ReplicaSet
metadata:
  name: my-replicaset
spec:
  replicas: 3  # Ensures 3 pods are always running
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app  # Matches pods with this label
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: my-app  # This must match the selector
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: my-container
        image: nginx
---
📌 Explanation:

 - replicas: 3 → Ensures 3 pods are running at all times.
 - selector.matchLabels.app: my-app → Selects pods labeled app: my-app.
 - template → Defines how the pod should be created if needed.

5️⃣ When Should You Use ReplicaSets?
✅ When you need basic pod replication without updates.
✅ When using a custom controller that requires ReplicaSet.
✅ When managing pods without using Deployments (not recommended).

🚀 However, in most cases, you should use Deployments instead of ReplicaSets!


